Container Management tools:
-> Openshift, apache marathon, docker swarm, docker compose 

Containerization:
-> The process of making a Container.

Container: 
-> A lightweight virtualisation method that packages an aplication along with its dependencies, libraries, and 
   configuration files into a single, portable unit called Container.
-> It shares the host machine's kernel, making them efficient and fast.
-> Characteristics: Isolation, portability, lightweight, fast setup, standarisation.
-> virtual machine requires sub-operating system while containers shares machine's kernel.
-> Benefits: Consistency, resource efficiency, scalability, Devops integration, microservices ready.
-> In 2026, the landscape is divided into three main categories: Container Engines (creating/running), Orchestrators (managing at scale), and Supporting Tools (security and networking).
-> Container Engines : Docker, Podman(Daemonless, rootless, pod support, docker compatible), containered, CRI-O.
    -> Podman commnds eg: podman run -dt -p 8080:80 <image> , podman pull <image>,podman rm <name_or_id>, etc.
-> Core Docker Components: Docker CLient, Docker Daemon, Docker Images, Docker Containers, Docker Registry.
-> Common Docker Commands:
1. Working with Containers (Lifecycle)
    docker run <image>: It pulls the image (if missing), creates a container, and starts it.
        -d: Runs in "detached" mode (background).
        -p 8080:80: Maps host port 8080 to container port 80.
        --name my-app: Gives your container a custom name.
    docker ps: Lists all running containers. Use docker ps -a to see all containers, including stopped ones.
    docker stop <id/name>: Gracefully shuts down a container.
    docker start <id/name>: Restarts a stopped container.
    docker exec -it <id/name> bash: Opens an interactive terminal inside a running container. (Use sh if bash isn't available).
    docker logs -f <id/name>: Views the output/logs of a container in real-time.
2. Managing Images
    docker build -t my-image:v1 .: Builds an image from a Dockerfile in the current directory (.) and tags it.
    docker images: Lists all images currently stored on your machine.
    docker pull <image>: Downloads an image from Docker Hub without running it.
    docker push <user/image>: Uploads your local image to a registry like Docker Hub.
    docker rmi <image-id>: Deletes a specific image from your machine.

3. Storage & Networking
    docker volume ls: Lists all persistent data volumes.
    docker volume create <name>: Manually creates a storage area.
    docker network ls: Lists networks (Bridge, Host, etc.) that containers use to talk to each other.
    docker inspect <id>: Shows detailed JSON information about a container, including its IP address and mount points.

4. Cleanup & Maintenance
    docker rm <id>: Removes a specific stopped container.
    docker system prune: The "nuclear option." It deletes all stopped containers, unused networks, and "dangling" images to free up space.
    docker stats: Displays a live stream of CPU and memory usage for all running containers.